  "prompt": "Is spot counselling for reserved candidates?",
  "response": "Spot counselling is typically conducted for candidates who have either:\n\n1. Not been allotted a seat during the initial rounds of counselling\n2. Not participated in the earlier counselling rounds\n3. If seats remain vacant after the main counselling process\n\nWhile spot counselling is generally open to all candidates, including reserved and general category candidates, the specific rules can vary depending on the counselling authority and the specific admission process. Reserved category candidates do get certain benefits and relaxations during spot counselling, such as:\n\n1. Reservation quota seats\n2. Lower cut-off marks\n3. Age relaxation in some cases\n\nThe exact details depend on:\n- The specific institution\n- The admission process\n- State/central government rules\n- Type of course\n\nTo get precise information about spot counselling for reserved candidates, it's best to:\n- Check the official counselling website\n- Read the counselling brochure\n- Contact the counselling authority directly\n\nEach counselling process has its own specific guidelines, so verifying the current year's rules is recommended.",
